# Web route shape — Umbraculum β disciplines

Authored 2026-05-21 as part of the Week-1 web-route audit (see umbraculum-dev
`docs/design/web-route-group-audit.md` + `docs/rfcs/0006-amend-rfc-0002-brewery-file-move-acceleration.md`).
Codifies the two physical-layout disciplines and the URL-segment ownership
contract that the audit ratified.

## The shape (β filesystem-axis)

```
apps/web/app/[locale]/
├─ page.tsx                      ← Dashboard ONLY (the locale-root home)
├─ (auth)/                       ← Platform grouping route group
│  ├─ login/page.tsx             ← /en/login
│  ├─ signup/page.tsx            ← /en/signup
│  └─ select-workspace/page.tsx  ← /en/select-workspace
├─ (automation)/                 ← Canonical-module route group (code: "automation")
│  └─ vessels/                   ← Owned static sub-segment (registered via registerWebModule)
│     ├─ page.tsx                ← /en/vessels
│     └─ [vesselCode]/page.tsx   ← /en/vessels/<code>
├─ (pim)/                        ← Canonical-module route group (code: "pim")
│  ├─ products/page.tsx          ← /en/products
│  ├─ products/[productId]/page.tsx
│  ├─ categories/page.tsx
│  ├─ attribute-sets/page.tsx
│  └─ attribute-sets/[setId]/page.tsx
└─ (brewery)/                    ← Canonical-module route group (code: "brewery")
   ├─ recipes/...
   ├─ inventory/page.tsx
   └─ ...
```

Route groups (`(name)/`) **do not** contribute a URL segment per Next.js App
Router semantics. URLs are flat under `[locale]/` regardless of which group
the page lives under.

## The two β disciplines (hard rules)

### Discipline 1 — No `(code)/page.tsx` at the route-group root

A `page.tsx` file directly inside any route group at the `[locale]/` level
**collides** with `[locale]/page.tsx` (the locale-root home / Dashboard).
Both files resolve to the URL `/en` — Next.js picks one at build time
("Conflicting public file and page file") and the other vanishes from the
routing table without warning at runtime, depending on bundler resolution
order.

**Bad** (was deployed pre-audit; broke `/en` for some sessions):

```
apps/web/app/[locale]/(automation)/page.tsx   ← ❌ collides with [locale]/page.tsx
```

**Good**:

```
apps/web/app/[locale]/(automation)/vessels/page.tsx   ← /en/vessels
apps/web/app/[locale]/page.tsx                        ← /en (Dashboard, sole owner)
```

### Discipline 2 — No `(code)/[dynamicSegment]/page.tsx` at the route-group root

A dynamic segment file (`[foo]/page.tsx`) directly inside a route group at
the `[locale]/` level **shadows** every other module's static segments.
Next.js routes `/en/anything` to that dynamic page because dynamic
segments match anything that isn't a literal static-segment match — and
the locale-root has no static-segment competitors at the route-group-root
level.

**Bad** (was deployed pre-audit; `/en/login`, `/en/recipes`, `/en/FAKE-CODE`
all rendered the Vessel-Detail page silently):

```
apps/web/app/[locale]/(automation)/[vesselCode]/page.tsx   ← ❌ shadows everything
```

**Good**:

```
apps/web/app/[locale]/(automation)/vessels/[vesselCode]/page.tsx   ← only matches /en/vessels/*
```

## URL-segment ownership (D2 — full reservation)

Every canonical module declares the top-level URL segments it owns via
`@umbraculum/module-sdk`'s `registerWebModule()`:

```typescript
// services/api/src/modules/pim/index.ts (example)
registerWebModule({
  code: "pim",
  ownedUrlSegments: ["products", "categories", "attribute-sets"],
  navEntry: { primarySegment: "products", labelKey: "nav.pim" },
});
```

Rules:

- Every static sub-segment under `apps/web/app/[locale]/(<code>)/<segment>/`
  must appear in the module's `ownedUrlSegments` array.
- Every segment must match `/^[a-z][a-z0-9-]*$/` (kebab-case, leading letter).
- A segment cannot be claimed by two modules — `UrlSegmentAlreadyOwnedError`
  is thrown at registration time.
- `navEntry.primarySegment` (if provided) must be one of `ownedUrlSegments`.

The platform itself registers the residual non-canonical-module segments
(`login`, `signup`, `select-account`, `select-workspace`, `ai`, `platform`,
`about`, `contact`, `accessibility`, `contributing`, `i18n-contributing`)
via `apps/web/app/_lib/registerPlatformSegments.ts` under the pseudo-code
`"platform"`. Auth segments live under the platform-grouping route group
`(auth)/`; the rest are flat folders under `[locale]/`.

## CI gate

`scripts/check-web-url-segments.ts` enforces all of the above at build
time. The script is wired into `.github/workflows/check-web-url-segments.yml`
and reports four issue classes:

1. `discipline-1-group-root-page` — group has a `page.tsx` at the route-group root
2. `discipline-2-group-root-dynamic` — group has `[<segment>]/page.tsx` at the route-group root
3. `static-segment-not-registered` — folder exists under `(<code>)/<segment>/` but `<segment>` is not in `KNOWN_MODULE_OWNERSHIP[<code>]`
4. `flat-module-folder` — module folder exists flat under `[locale]/` (instead of inside a `(<code>)/` route group), AND the folder name is not in `PLATFORM_RESERVED_SEGMENTS`

The script does NOT auto-fix; it reports. Fixes are mechanical (move files
into the correct route group + update the module's `registerWebModule` call).

## When this rule fires

Authoring or reviewing any of:

- `apps/web/app/[locale]/(*)/page.tsx` — STOP, this is Discipline 1 violation
- `apps/web/app/[locale]/(*)/[<dyn>]/page.tsx` — STOP, this is Discipline 2 violation
- A new flat folder `apps/web/app/[locale]/<X>/` for a canonical-module concern — STOP, move under `(<code>)/<X>/`
- A new `registerWebModule()` call — verify `ownedUrlSegments` matches the
  folder structure and that the segments are not collision-prone
- A new RouteId in `packages/navigation/src/index.ts` — verify the path in
  `routeToPath` matches the owned segment, not the module code

## Forward-looking note

The Week-1 audit grew `packages/navigation`'s `RouteId` enum + `routeToPath`
with seven module-specific entries (`vessels`, `vesselDetail`, `products`,
`productDetail`, `categories`, `attributeSets`, `attributeSetDetail`). A
follow-on RFC ("module-driven navigation registry", to be authored after
Week 1 lands) will refactor `packages/navigation` to derive these from
`@umbraculum/module-sdk`'s `listRegisteredWebModules()` so the navigation
package no longer ships per-module branches. Until that RFC lands, every
new canonical-module route requires:

1. Adding the segment to the module's `registerWebModule({ ownedUrlSegments })`
2. Adding the RouteId + RouteParamsById + routeToPath branch in `packages/navigation/src/index.ts`
3. Adding (or extending) the corresponding case in `packages/navigation/src/native.ts` (throw "web-only" if native has no screen yet)

## Why this fits the system (per umbraculum-toolset authoring gate)

**Frontier-now**: keeps the AI agent from re-introducing the two specific
anti-patterns the Week-1 audit fixed. Both anti-patterns produce silent
runtime breakage that browser smoke-tests would have to catch — they
don't surface in unit tests. The rule is the cheap front-door defense;
`scripts/check-web-url-segments.ts` is the CI fallback when the rule is
ignored.

**Local-subagent-future**: paired with the (to-be-authored) `web-route-shape-checker`
subagent that runs `npm run check-web-url-segments` and returns a bounded
OK/FAIL summary — same shape as `types-baseline-verifier` and
`module-readme-checker` already in this plugin. The subagent shell exists
in `scripts/check-web-url-segments.ts`; the subagent wrapper is deferred to
the post-Week-1 lessons-addendum pass.
